1
00:00:35,121 --> 00:00:37,281
DOCTOR: Planet Earth.

2
00:00:37,401 --> 00:00:41,321
Early in the third decade
of the 21st century.

3
00:00:41,441 --> 00:00:45,081
Population - seven billion.

4
00:00:45,201 --> 00:00:50,121
Seven billion lives,
separate and connected.

5
00:00:52,361 --> 00:00:54,521
From the depths
of the oceans...

6
00:00:54,641 --> 00:00:56,481
(WHOOSHING)

7
00:00:57,641 --> 00:01:00,641
...to the edge
of the atmosphere.

8
00:01:00,761 --> 00:01:02,281
- (RUMBLING)
- (ALARMS BLARE)

9
00:01:04,201 --> 00:01:07,601
Soyuz to Control, we have
automatic system failure.

10
00:01:07,721 --> 00:01:10,001
CONTROL: Copy that, Soyuz.
Can you switch

11
00:01:10,121 --> 00:01:12,521
to ballistic descent
and maintain trajectory?

12
00:01:12,641 --> 00:01:14,681
Negative. I'm way off course.

13
00:01:14,801 --> 00:01:16,641
DMP's failed.

14
00:01:16,761 --> 00:01:19,641
And we have to deploy
the parachute!

15
00:01:19,761 --> 00:01:21,801
(GASPS AND GRUNTS)

16
00:01:21,921 --> 00:01:23,961
Control, do you copy?

17
00:01:26,561 --> 00:01:28,521
(GROANS)

18
00:01:28,641 --> 00:01:29,961
(CRASH)

19
00:01:40,041 --> 00:01:42,001
You, my friend,
are under arrest.

20
00:01:43,521 --> 00:01:45,201
You do not
have to say anything,

21
00:01:45,321 --> 00:01:46,481
but anything you do say

22
00:01:46,601 --> 00:01:48,161
may seriously aggravate me.

23
00:01:48,281 --> 00:01:49,721
Jake, what are you doing?!

24
00:01:51,361 --> 00:01:52,561
Nailed him.

25
00:01:53,721 --> 00:01:56,521
(INDISTINCT
TANNOY ANNOUNCEMENT)

26
00:01:56,641 --> 00:01:58,841
I can't believe
you're letting him walk away.

27
00:01:58,961 --> 00:02:02,721
You can't go round
rugby-tackling kids like that!

28
00:02:02,841 --> 00:02:04,961
You're not a police officer,
Jake.

29
00:02:05,081 --> 00:02:06,281
Yes, I am!

30
00:02:06,401 --> 00:02:08,241
I'm just...on a break.

31
00:02:09,441 --> 00:02:10,761
Getting my head straight.

32
00:02:11,801 --> 00:02:14,161
This really isn't working out,
is it?

33
00:02:17,121 --> 00:02:19,001
Obrigada!

34
00:02:21,961 --> 00:02:23,481
- Close your eyes.
- Why?

35
00:02:23,601 --> 00:02:24,841
Trust me!

36
00:02:24,961 --> 00:02:27,201
You're gonna love this.

37
00:02:27,321 --> 00:02:30,641
This is the most beautiful
river in the world.

38
00:02:33,561 --> 00:02:34,961
OK.

39
00:02:39,521 --> 00:02:41,281
(BIRDS SQUAWKING)

40
00:02:42,521 --> 00:02:44,401
(FLIES BUZZING)

41
00:02:47,001 --> 00:02:48,441
(PLASTIC CRUNCHES UNDERFOOT)

42
00:02:50,321 --> 00:02:51,761
Is this a joke?

43
00:02:51,881 --> 00:02:53,321
It's wrecked.

44
00:02:53,441 --> 00:02:54,401
(BIRDS SQUAWKING)

45
00:02:54,521 --> 00:02:56,161
I don't know what happened.
Three years ago,

46
00:02:56,281 --> 00:02:57,921
this was paradise.

47
00:02:58,041 --> 00:02:59,401
Gabriela,
there's no way in hell

48
00:02:59,521 --> 00:03:01,081
we're camping here tonight.

49
00:03:02,641 --> 00:03:04,361
(LOUD SNORING)

50
00:03:07,681 --> 00:03:08,761
Every time.

51
00:03:08,881 --> 00:03:10,401
(FLUTTERING)

52
00:03:16,361 --> 00:03:18,081
(FLUTTERING)

53
00:03:25,401 --> 00:03:28,161
(BIRDS SQUAWKING)

54
00:03:34,481 --> 00:03:35,281
Oh!

55
00:03:37,361 --> 00:03:38,681
Ugh.

56
00:03:41,801 --> 00:03:43,921
(SQUAWKING INTENSIFIES)

57
00:03:45,961 --> 00:03:47,881
(SQUAWKING INTENSIFIES)

58
00:03:48,001 --> 00:03:49,801
(SCREAMS)

59
00:03:51,801 --> 00:03:53,241
TV: Another win for Liverpool

60
00:03:53,361 --> 00:03:56,561
has seen them increase pressure
on their title rivals

61
00:03:56,681 --> 00:03:57,961
Manchester City.

62
00:03:58,081 --> 00:04:02,401
Now, I'm just hearing that
we have some breaking news.

63
00:04:02,521 --> 00:04:03,961
Mate, can you turn that up?

64
00:04:04,081 --> 00:04:06,641
A statement just issued by
the European Space Agency

65
00:04:06,761 --> 00:04:10,321
says they're still unable
to confirm whether

66
00:04:10,441 --> 00:04:12,641
the British astronaut Adam Lang

67
00:04:12,761 --> 00:04:16,081
managed to evacuate
his descent module safely

68
00:04:16,201 --> 00:04:17,801
after it veered off course

69
00:04:17,921 --> 00:04:20,921
and crashed into
the Indian Ocean earlier today.

70
00:04:21,041 --> 00:04:23,681
Although
search and rescue teams

71
00:04:23,801 --> 00:04:27,081
continue to trawl the waters,
the Agency say

72
00:04:27,201 --> 00:04:32,361
they are now treating Adam Lang
as missing, presumed dead.

73
00:04:32,481 --> 00:04:35,241
There are tributes for Mr Lang
on social media

74
00:04:35,361 --> 00:04:37,201
- and his family have asked...
- (PHONE VIBRATES)

75
00:04:37,321 --> 00:04:40,481
...for privacy at what they say
ls a difficult time.

76
00:04:40,601 --> 00:04:42,041
(TV FADES OUT)

77
00:04:51,761 --> 00:04:53,321
(MESSAGE SENT ALERT)

78
00:05:19,921 --> 00:05:21,121
Jamila!

79
00:05:21,241 --> 00:05:23,881
(SHOUT ECHOES)

80
00:05:24,001 --> 00:05:24,801
(CRASH)

81
00:05:24,921 --> 00:05:26,281
What the hell?

82
00:05:30,681 --> 00:05:32,801
That's weird.

83
00:05:35,641 --> 00:05:36,721
Hey!

84
00:05:36,841 --> 00:05:38,121
Don't touch it.

85
00:05:38,241 --> 00:05:40,201
Something's wrong
with the birds.

86
00:05:54,441 --> 00:05:57,441
PHONE: You have arrived
at your destination.

87
00:05:59,201 --> 00:06:00,561
(DOG BARKING)

88
00:06:03,441 --> 00:06:05,081
(BUZZES)

89
00:06:05,201 --> 00:06:08,601
(BUZZES RHYTHMICALLY)

90
00:06:19,481 --> 00:06:21,641
YAZ: I don't think
they're too keen on visitors!

91
00:06:21,761 --> 00:06:23,841
Come on, son, fists down.

92
00:06:23,961 --> 00:06:26,001
There's a good lad.

93
00:06:26,121 --> 00:06:27,681
Now, perhaps you'd like
to tell us

94
00:06:27,801 --> 00:06:29,681
why you're so interested
in that door.

95
00:06:32,001 --> 00:06:33,481
DI Jake Willis.

96
00:06:33,601 --> 00:06:35,041
I've reason to believe
there may be

97
00:06:35,161 --> 00:06:36,601
a missing person
inside that building.

98
00:06:36,721 --> 00:06:38,561
Bit out of your jurisdiction,
this.

99
00:06:38,681 --> 00:06:40,001
Sorry, who are you?

100
00:06:41,281 --> 00:06:43,201
We're the people...

101
00:06:43,321 --> 00:06:46,161
...with a nice big set
of skeleton keys.

102
00:06:58,041 --> 00:06:59,121
Good morning, Suki.

103
00:06:59,241 --> 00:07:00,561
Sleep in?

104
00:07:01,881 --> 00:07:03,521
One day I will get here
before you.

105
00:07:03,641 --> 00:07:05,921
(LAUGHS) But I'm always
ready for work.

106
00:07:06,041 --> 00:07:07,761
Especially work like this.

107
00:07:07,881 --> 00:07:09,881
(YELLING) Need some help
over here!

108
00:07:21,561 --> 00:07:22,921
Hi!

109
00:07:23,041 --> 00:07:24,521
(GASPS) Why is it always

110
00:07:24,641 --> 00:07:26,361
the big lads
that need rescuing?

111
00:07:26,481 --> 00:07:27,921
Oh, thanks.

112
00:07:28,041 --> 00:07:29,921
I normally have my mates
with me.

113
00:07:30,041 --> 00:07:31,041
I gave them all errands.

114
00:07:32,961 --> 00:07:33,921
If you touched Jamila...

115
00:07:34,041 --> 00:07:35,001
Hey, I don't even know
who Jamila is.

116
00:07:35,121 --> 00:07:36,041
She vanished.

117
00:07:36,161 --> 00:07:37,121
And you are the only

118
00:07:37,241 --> 00:07:38,481
- other person out here.
- OK.

119
00:07:38,601 --> 00:07:40,201
But I swear I haven't seen her.

120
00:07:40,321 --> 00:07:42,401
I'm here because of
what's wrong with the birds.

121
00:07:42,521 --> 00:07:43,441
You think I'll buy that?

122
00:07:43,561 --> 00:07:44,681
You should,
because it's the truth.

123
00:07:44,801 --> 00:07:46,681
Look, I'm not armed.
There's nothing in my bag.

124
00:07:46,801 --> 00:07:48,481
Check yourself
if you don't believe me.

125
00:07:52,681 --> 00:07:54,441
How long has she been gone?

126
00:07:54,561 --> 00:07:57,601
I last saw her before
I went to sleep last night.

127
00:07:58,881 --> 00:07:59,921
Stand still.

128
00:08:01,961 --> 00:08:03,241
Have you tried her phone?

129
00:08:03,361 --> 00:08:06,521
Of course I tried her phone.
I tried her on everything.

130
00:08:06,641 --> 00:08:09,081
I just messaged some contacts
on Reddit

131
00:08:09,201 --> 00:08:11,361
to access emergency services
and satellites.

132
00:08:12,721 --> 00:08:13,721
Ooh.

133
00:08:14,921 --> 00:08:16,041
You work out?

134
00:08:17,281 --> 00:08:18,921
I do a lot of running.

135
00:08:20,961 --> 00:08:22,601
I'm Gabriela.

136
00:08:23,481 --> 00:08:25,241
I'm guessing you know that.

137
00:08:25,361 --> 00:08:26,921
No.

138
00:08:27,041 --> 00:08:28,201
Two Girls Roaming?

139
00:08:30,361 --> 00:08:31,361
The travel vlog!

140
00:08:31,481 --> 00:08:33,161
That's me and Jamila.

141
00:08:33,281 --> 00:08:36,481
Sorry. Bit behind. I do a fair
bit of travelling myself.

142
00:08:36,601 --> 00:08:38,081
I'm Ryan.

143
00:08:38,201 --> 00:08:40,321
Need to take that bird.
These markings -

144
00:08:40,441 --> 00:08:41,881
they're not natural.

145
00:08:45,921 --> 00:08:47,801
What are you doing?

146
00:08:47,921 --> 00:08:49,761
Birds are falling
out of the sky.

147
00:08:49,881 --> 00:08:51,641
I'm trying to find out
the reason.

148
00:08:51,761 --> 00:08:52,961
(PHONE ALERT)

149
00:08:54,841 --> 00:08:56,321
That her?

150
00:08:57,601 --> 00:08:58,761
No.

151
00:08:58,881 --> 00:08:59,881
But someone's found out

152
00:09:00,001 --> 00:09:02,441
there was an emergency call-out
this morning.

153
00:09:03,441 --> 00:09:04,801
One mile away.

154
00:09:07,521 --> 00:09:09,841
Ambulancia.

155
00:09:11,281 --> 00:09:12,441
JAKE: So who are you?

156
00:09:12,561 --> 00:09:14,721
Interpol?

157
00:09:14,841 --> 00:09:16,521
Did the ESA send you?

158
00:09:16,641 --> 00:09:17,921
ESA?

159
00:09:18,041 --> 00:09:20,241
European Space Agency.

160
00:09:20,361 --> 00:09:21,641
To find
their missing astronaut?

161
00:09:23,361 --> 00:09:25,001
Your missing person's
an astronaut?

162
00:09:25,121 --> 00:09:26,321
Adam Lang.

163
00:09:26,441 --> 00:09:27,761
Equipment failure
coming back from

164
00:09:27,881 --> 00:09:29,081
the International
Space Station.

165
00:09:29,201 --> 00:09:30,121
It's all over the ne...

166
00:09:30,241 --> 00:09:32,241
You're not even
looking for him, are you?

167
00:09:32,361 --> 00:09:34,641
There's some very unusual
energy patterns

168
00:09:34,761 --> 00:09:35,921
coming from this building.

169
00:09:36,041 --> 00:09:37,281
We're under instructions

170
00:09:37,401 --> 00:09:38,881
- to find out why.
- A man's gone missing

171
00:09:39,001 --> 00:09:41,401
and nobody's doing anything
to find him.

172
00:09:41,521 --> 00:09:42,681
Apart from you.

173
00:09:42,801 --> 00:09:44,761
The police.

174
00:09:46,601 --> 00:09:47,641
Yeah.

175
00:09:49,201 --> 00:09:51,201
(LABOURED BREATHING)

176
00:09:53,841 --> 00:09:55,241
DOCTOR: Right.
Let's put him down.

177
00:09:56,841 --> 00:09:58,641
This is a US naval uniform.

178
00:09:58,761 --> 00:10:00,321
- What's he doing here?
- A US submarine

179
00:10:00,441 --> 00:10:02,401
went missing
in the Indian Ocean.

180
00:10:02,521 --> 00:10:04,761
I've been checking the tide
patterns for survivors.

181
00:10:05,961 --> 00:10:07,041
I'm the Doctor, by the way.

182
00:10:07,161 --> 00:10:08,761
Aramu and Suki.

183
00:10:08,881 --> 00:10:10,961
Nice to meet you both.
You live here?

184
00:10:11,081 --> 00:10:12,641
Work here. That's my lab.

185
00:10:12,761 --> 00:10:13,961
We could get him inside and...

186
00:10:14,081 --> 00:10:15,721
(GASPS)

187
00:10:15,841 --> 00:10:17,081
- Help me!
- It's all right!

188
00:10:17,201 --> 00:10:18,601
You're safe!

189
00:10:18,721 --> 00:10:21,321
- No... No, I'm not...
- What's your name?

190
00:10:21,441 --> 00:10:23,041
Zach Olson.

191
00:10:23,161 --> 00:10:24,481
There was an impact.

192
00:10:24,601 --> 00:10:27,241
Our captain tried to raise
the sub, but it was too late.

193
00:10:27,361 --> 00:10:29,281
It was already inside.

194
00:10:29,401 --> 00:10:31,121
What was already inside, Zach?

195
00:10:31,241 --> 00:10:32,681
(CRUNCHING)

196
00:10:32,801 --> 00:10:33,841
No!

197
00:10:33,961 --> 00:10:35,161
What's on his hand?

198
00:10:35,281 --> 00:10:36,601
Oh, no!

199
00:10:36,721 --> 00:10:38,801
No! No!

200
00:10:44,801 --> 00:10:46,041
OK.

201
00:10:46,161 --> 00:10:49,641
So, with the understanding
that was pretty alarming...

202
00:10:51,041 --> 00:10:52,441
...don't be overly alarmed.

203
00:10:52,561 --> 00:10:54,201
His body just disintegrated.

204
00:10:54,321 --> 00:10:56,401
Yes. Poor man.

205
00:10:56,521 --> 00:10:58,041
How is that even possible?

206
00:10:58,161 --> 00:10:59,361
I don't know.

207
00:10:59,481 --> 00:11:02,521
There's a connection between
all these things. I just...

208
00:11:02,641 --> 00:11:04,241
Argh, I just can't see it yet.

209
00:11:04,361 --> 00:11:06,481
- Between what things?
- A missing submarine,

210
00:11:06,601 --> 00:11:09,201
a dead naval officer
off the coast of Madagascar,

211
00:11:09,321 --> 00:11:12,081
birds going haywire in Peru,

212
00:11:12,201 --> 00:11:14,121
and active alien tech
in Hong Kong.

213
00:11:14,241 --> 00:11:16,641
There's also a talking cat
in Ontario,

214
00:11:16,761 --> 00:11:18,321
but I've ruled him out for now.

215
00:11:20,281 --> 00:11:21,321
What?

216
00:11:21,441 --> 00:11:23,761
You just said...alien.

217
00:11:26,121 --> 00:11:28,761
This is the hospital
the ambulance brought her to.

218
00:11:33,881 --> 00:11:36,041
RYAN: Hello?

219
00:11:37,441 --> 00:11:38,881
Hello?

220
00:11:48,801 --> 00:11:51,961
(DOORS CREAK)

221
00:11:54,321 --> 00:11:55,561
Where are all the staff?

222
00:12:02,001 --> 00:12:04,001
- RYAN: Another one in here.
- What are you doing?

223
00:12:06,801 --> 00:12:08,521
The same as the river.

224
00:12:09,681 --> 00:12:10,961
(CLANG)

225
00:12:29,321 --> 00:12:31,441
Hey! The whole point
of quarantine

226
00:12:31,561 --> 00:12:33,081
is not going in
where it says "quarantine”.

227
00:12:33,201 --> 00:12:34,441
Do you want to find her or not?

228
00:12:36,481 --> 00:12:38,521
(DOORS CREAK)

229
00:12:47,801 --> 00:12:49,121
Tell me that's not her.

230
00:13:03,641 --> 00:13:04,921
(GASPS)

231
00:13:06,241 --> 00:13:07,841
Jamila!

232
00:13:07,961 --> 00:13:09,201
I'm sorry.

233
00:13:15,361 --> 00:13:16,801
Melhor amiga.

234
00:13:21,841 --> 00:13:23,201
Doctor?

235
00:13:23,321 --> 00:13:25,921
I've found something
that you'll wanna see.

236
00:13:26,041 --> 00:13:27,441
Who are you talking to?

237
00:13:27,561 --> 00:13:30,001
How are you calling a doctor?

238
00:13:33,401 --> 00:13:35,721
RYAN: You've seen
these markings before...

239
00:13:37,761 --> 00:13:39,121
(GASPS)

240
00:13:39,241 --> 00:13:40,681
(CRUNCHING)

241
00:13:40,801 --> 00:13:41,721
GABRIELA: Jamila!

242
00:13:41,841 --> 00:13:43,241
Hey, get away from her!

243
00:13:43,361 --> 00:13:45,641
No! She's alive!

244
00:13:45,761 --> 00:13:47,721
- (CRUNCHING)
- (SPEAKS PORTUGUESE)

245
00:13:47,841 --> 00:13:48,841
I don't think that's alive.

246
00:13:48,961 --> 00:13:49,881
We have to help her!

247
00:13:50,001 --> 00:13:51,201
No, Ryan's right.
She's not alive.

248
00:13:51,321 --> 00:13:54,121
Whatever caused her death seems
to still be attacking her body.

249
00:13:54,241 --> 00:13:55,961
- Who are you?
- Doctor, her face.

250
00:13:56,081 --> 00:13:57,841
Yeah. I've just seen the same
thing on a naval officer

251
00:13:57,961 --> 00:13:59,841
- in Madagascar.
- (YELLS)

252
00:14:01,481 --> 00:14:03,441
(CRUNCHING)

253
00:14:09,041 --> 00:14:10,641
Jamila!

254
00:14:10,761 --> 00:14:11,961
Same as Zach on the beach.

255
00:14:12,081 --> 00:14:14,161
No, no, no,
this can't be happening.

256
00:14:14,281 --> 00:14:15,601
Hey, it's OK.

257
00:14:15,721 --> 00:14:17,041
- No, it's not!
- Two identical deaths

258
00:14:17,161 --> 00:14:18,841
on two different continents.

259
00:14:18,961 --> 00:14:20,761
It's even more dangerous
than I thought,

260
00:14:20,881 --> 00:14:22,121
and it's spreading.

261
00:14:22,241 --> 00:14:23,241
Which could mean...

262
00:14:24,361 --> 00:14:27,041
Have you heard
from Yaz and Graham?

263
00:14:30,001 --> 00:14:32,001
(BEEPING)

264
00:14:32,121 --> 00:14:33,641
Hey! Hey.

265
00:14:35,361 --> 00:14:38,441
Whatever is giving off
those weird readings...

266
00:14:40,081 --> 00:14:43,641
...is on the other side
of that wall.

267
00:14:47,201 --> 00:14:50,081
Is on the other side
of this door.

268
00:14:50,201 --> 00:14:51,961
You're welcome.

269
00:14:52,081 --> 00:14:53,721
(SIGHS)

270
00:14:55,601 --> 00:14:56,801
Locked from the inside.

271
00:14:56,921 --> 00:14:58,921
Maybe if we went round
the other way...

272
00:15:02,721 --> 00:15:04,441
Chat, chat, chat, chat, chat.

273
00:15:14,881 --> 00:15:16,361
What the hell's all this?

274
00:15:17,721 --> 00:15:20,161
Exactly what
we've been looking for.

275
00:15:30,361 --> 00:15:31,321
Adam?

276
00:15:31,441 --> 00:15:33,041
Adam!

277
00:15:33,161 --> 00:15:35,841
I told you he was here. I'm
gonna get this stuff off him.

278
00:15:35,961 --> 00:15:39,281
YAZ: Wait! Not until we know
what all this stuff is doing.

279
00:15:39,401 --> 00:15:41,201
No, Yaz is right. You can't
just go blundering in.

280
00:15:41,321 --> 00:15:42,361
You could end up killing him.

281
00:15:42,481 --> 00:15:43,721
How long's that going to take?

282
00:15:43,841 --> 00:15:45,481
We've been in this room
as long as you.

283
00:15:45,601 --> 00:15:49,961
Doctor, we found the source
of the energy.

284
00:15:50,081 --> 00:15:51,601
Plus a kidnapped astronaut.

285
00:15:51,721 --> 00:15:53,361
JAKE: Adam? Can you hear me?

286
00:15:53,481 --> 00:15:56,321
It's Jake. I'm here.
I'm here for you.

287
00:15:56,441 --> 00:15:58,241
I'm here.

288
00:15:59,881 --> 00:16:01,161
Get out.

289
00:16:01,281 --> 00:16:02,641
What?

290
00:16:02,761 --> 00:16:04,441
They'll come!

291
00:16:09,961 --> 00:16:11,721
GRAHAM: Unplug him
and get him out!

292
00:16:11,841 --> 00:16:13,881
You just said that wasn't safe!

293
00:16:14,001 --> 00:16:16,281
The situation's changed!
Get him out!

294
00:16:17,441 --> 00:16:18,801
Yaz, what are you doing?!

295
00:16:18,921 --> 00:16:20,801
Oi!

296
00:16:20,921 --> 00:16:22,361
Guns down, or I'll trash it.

297
00:16:22,481 --> 00:16:24,081
(LABOURED BREATHING)

298
00:16:24,201 --> 00:16:25,321
Hesitation.

299
00:16:25,441 --> 00:16:27,561
- Must be valuable.
- Yaz,

300
00:16:27,681 --> 00:16:29,481
we're out. Yaz, come on.

301
00:16:32,881 --> 00:16:34,361
Lads, keep going!

302
00:16:34,481 --> 00:16:35,521
They're right behind us.

303
00:16:35,641 --> 00:16:37,921
- You came.
- Course I came!

304
00:16:38,041 --> 00:16:40,641
Who are you with?
Can you get backup?

305
00:16:40,761 --> 00:16:42,321
Backup? Why would he
have backup?

306
00:16:42,441 --> 00:16:43,441
He's a copper!

307
00:16:43,561 --> 00:16:45,561
- Ex-copper.
- BOTH: What?

308
00:16:45,681 --> 00:16:47,401
- Can we not do this now?
- YAZ: Look out!

309
00:16:52,401 --> 00:16:53,481
- Down!
- Look out!

310
00:16:57,241 --> 00:16:58,721
I'm on a sabbatical.

311
00:16:58,841 --> 00:17:01,601
That's OK. So's she.

312
00:17:01,721 --> 00:17:04,241
Except I don't go around
announcing I'm police.

313
00:17:04,361 --> 00:17:06,081
Never believe anything he says.

314
00:17:06,201 --> 00:17:08,441
Mate, he's just come halfway
round the world to rescue you.

315
00:17:08,561 --> 00:17:09,561
Thank you!

316
00:17:09,681 --> 00:17:11,041
I scanned this building
for life signals

317
00:17:11,161 --> 00:17:13,521
before I sent you here,
so why didn't these register?

318
00:17:13,641 --> 00:17:15,441
- Doctor?
- Could be the suit

319
00:17:15,561 --> 00:17:17,401
- blocking the scan.
- JAKE: Is she with you?

320
00:17:17,521 --> 00:17:19,281
Uh! Can't get
the breathing apparatus off

321
00:17:19,401 --> 00:17:21,281
to see the face.

322
00:17:21,401 --> 00:17:23,241
Non-terrestrial.

323
00:17:23,361 --> 00:17:25,521
- Same as the weapon.
- Er...

324
00:17:26,681 --> 00:17:27,761
So, who are you?

325
00:17:27,881 --> 00:17:29,361
I'm the backup.

326
00:17:29,481 --> 00:17:32,481
Oh! Adam Lang.
Famous British astronaut.

327
00:17:32,601 --> 00:17:34,681
Famous missing
British astronaut.

328
00:17:34,801 --> 00:17:35,721
Glad you're safe.

329
00:17:35,841 --> 00:17:37,241
- How are you feeling?
- Terrible.

330
00:17:37,361 --> 00:17:38,441
Yeah, you look it.

331
00:17:38,561 --> 00:17:40,161
Hadn't factored you into this.

332
00:17:41,481 --> 00:17:43,081
Focused too much on that cat.

333
00:17:43,201 --> 00:17:46,361
This way. I'll introduce you
to Gabriela once we're inside.

334
00:17:46,481 --> 00:17:48,081
She's having a tough time
as well.

335
00:17:49,241 --> 00:17:50,561
Inside where?!

336
00:17:50,681 --> 00:17:52,561
Probably best
you see for yourself.

337
00:17:58,361 --> 00:18:01,441
Is it like, er,
an optical illusion?

338
00:18:02,681 --> 00:18:04,281
I really don't know.

339
00:18:08,761 --> 00:18:11,441
How long have you and Jamila
known each other?

340
00:18:11,561 --> 00:18:13,041
Five years.

341
00:18:16,481 --> 00:18:18,321
I don't know
what I'm going to do now.

342
00:18:18,441 --> 00:18:19,761
You'll get through it.

343
00:18:19,881 --> 00:18:21,961
Cos you've known me
for how many hours?

344
00:18:22,081 --> 00:18:24,241
We're going to find out
what happened.

345
00:18:24,361 --> 00:18:26,881
And we're going
to put it right.

346
00:18:29,481 --> 00:18:31,681
So you really don't believe
this thing travels?

347
00:18:38,961 --> 00:18:40,401
GABRIELA: No way.

348
00:18:44,321 --> 00:18:45,601
Through the doors!

349
00:18:45,721 --> 00:18:47,561
Past Ryan!

350
00:18:47,681 --> 00:18:48,401
We're not all going to fit

351
00:18:48,521 --> 00:18:49,441
- in there!
- You'd be surprised.

352
00:18:49,561 --> 00:18:51,321
Ryan, this is Jake and Adam.

353
00:18:51,441 --> 00:18:52,601
DOCTOR: Come on, Yaz!

354
00:18:52,721 --> 00:18:54,441
- No.
- Sorry?

355
00:18:54,561 --> 00:18:56,921
There was a device in there.
I couldn't get it free in time.

356
00:18:57,041 --> 00:18:58,281
It looked really important
to them.

357
00:18:58,401 --> 00:18:59,321
I want to go back and get it.

358
00:18:59,441 --> 00:19:01,721
- We don't have enough time.
- You go. Come back for me in,

359
00:19:01,841 --> 00:19:03,241
I don't know,
an hour or something.

360
00:19:03,361 --> 00:19:04,401
It's too dangerous.

361
00:19:04,521 --> 00:19:05,801
We need to know
why Adam was taken there

362
00:19:05,921 --> 00:19:06,881
and what they did to him,

363
00:19:07,001 --> 00:19:09,281
and how this is all connected
to those other events.

364
00:19:09,401 --> 00:19:12,521
I'll come with you. I'm more
than ready to fight something.

365
00:19:15,161 --> 00:19:16,161
One hour.

366
00:19:23,241 --> 00:19:25,761
Hey, I'm Gabriela.
You must be Yaz.

367
00:19:25,881 --> 00:19:27,721
YAZ: Come on.
It's through here.

368
00:19:31,281 --> 00:19:33,241
So the box is the doorway
to this building?

369
00:19:33,361 --> 00:19:35,401
No building.
You're still in the box.

370
00:19:35,521 --> 00:19:37,361
But...the box was smaller
than this.

371
00:19:37,481 --> 00:19:38,441
The inside of the box

372
00:19:38,561 --> 00:19:40,681
- is bigger than the outside.
- That's not possible.

373
00:19:40,801 --> 00:19:42,441
It clearly is,
cos you're in it.

374
00:19:42,561 --> 00:19:44,041
It's a space- and time-ship,
mate.

375
00:19:44,161 --> 00:19:45,721
- Don't be stupid.
- Well, excuse me,

376
00:19:45,841 --> 00:19:48,881
Inspector Morse, but I ain't
the fantasist round here.

377
00:19:49,001 --> 00:19:50,761
Adam, you really
don't look well.

378
00:19:50,881 --> 00:19:52,041
I need to do an MOT.

379
00:19:52,161 --> 00:19:53,201
(GROANS)

380
00:19:54,841 --> 00:19:56,961
- Ow!
- I did say it would hurt.

381
00:19:57,081 --> 00:19:58,361
- No, you didn't.
- Well, I meant to.

382
00:19:58,481 --> 00:20:01,561
It takes a blood sample
for analysis.

383
00:20:01,681 --> 00:20:05,041
So...International
Space Station.

384
00:20:05,161 --> 00:20:07,921
- Was it awesome?
- Really awesome.

385
00:20:08,041 --> 00:20:09,241
Best bits?

386
00:20:09,361 --> 00:20:11,761
Just watching the planet turn
across a day.

387
00:20:11,881 --> 00:20:13,801
The aurora borealis.

388
00:20:13,921 --> 00:20:17,521
Seeing hurricanes start to form
from above.

389
00:20:17,641 --> 00:20:22,201
It just changes how you...
see everything.

390
00:20:24,041 --> 00:20:25,001
(RINGTONE BEEPS)

391
00:20:25,121 --> 00:20:27,001
Incoming call.

392
00:20:27,121 --> 00:20:29,121
SUKI: Is this the Doctor?

393
00:20:29,241 --> 00:20:31,241
Aramu. Suki.
Everything all right?

394
00:20:31,361 --> 00:20:34,161
You said to call if anything
else unusual happened.

395
00:20:34,281 --> 00:20:35,281
(TARDIS THRUMS)

396
00:20:38,561 --> 00:20:39,641
ARAMU: Suki?

397
00:20:39,761 --> 00:20:41,841
This is not an ordinary day.

398
00:20:41,961 --> 00:20:45,121
No. Very not ordinary.

399
00:20:46,241 --> 00:20:47,481
Before you show me unusual,

400
00:20:47,601 --> 00:20:49,561
can me and my friends
make use of your lab?

401
00:20:49,681 --> 00:20:51,641
- SUKI: Where did you go?
- Busy day.

402
00:20:54,561 --> 00:20:56,521
Still can't believe
what we saw earlier.

403
00:20:56,641 --> 00:20:59,161
He's not the first person
to die like that today.

404
00:20:59,281 --> 00:21:01,801
Same thing happened
to a young woman in Peru.

405
00:21:01,921 --> 00:21:04,441
They're linked.
I need to work out how.

406
00:21:04,561 --> 00:21:06,121
Plus, we've got
a sick astronaut

407
00:21:06,241 --> 00:21:07,681
getting sicker by the moment.

408
00:21:07,801 --> 00:21:10,561
So, you two know
each other how?

409
00:21:10,681 --> 00:21:12,521
- We're separated.
- We're married.

410
00:21:12,641 --> 00:21:14,881
Well, one of yous
is in for a shock.

411
00:21:15,001 --> 00:21:17,321
One of us doesn't like
putting the work in.

412
00:21:17,441 --> 00:21:19,481
I came halfway round the world.

413
00:21:19,601 --> 00:21:21,081
Seven months too late.

414
00:21:21,201 --> 00:21:25,481
Boys! Maybe now is not
the moment. Let's get inside.

415
00:21:25,601 --> 00:21:28,401
Come on, son. You can do it.
A few more steps.

416
00:21:28,521 --> 00:21:31,241
DOCTOR: The birds are
looking wrong here, too.

417
00:21:31,361 --> 00:21:33,441
ARAMU: I only saw it
the past few days.

418
00:21:33,561 --> 00:21:35,601
At first I thought

419
00:21:35,721 --> 00:21:36,721
it was OK, you know.

420
00:21:36,841 --> 00:21:39,361
It's not the first bird
to fly off its course.

421
00:21:39,481 --> 00:21:41,401
It's not native to Madagascar?

422
00:21:41,521 --> 00:21:43,001
No.

423
00:21:43,121 --> 00:21:46,081
Hey. Don't get too close.

424
00:21:46,201 --> 00:21:47,881
That's not the only one.

425
00:21:48,001 --> 00:21:49,401
Others...

426
00:21:50,441 --> 00:21:52,521
...have started to come.

427
00:21:52,641 --> 00:21:53,961
DOCTOR: Yes, they have.

428
00:21:54,081 --> 00:21:55,801
But why here?

429
00:21:57,161 --> 00:21:59,921
RYAN: There was a dead bird
in that deserted hospital,

430
00:22:00,041 --> 00:22:01,361
and all over the dumping ground

431
00:22:01,481 --> 00:22:03,241
where Gabriela and Jamila
were camping.

432
00:22:03,361 --> 00:22:05,561
And now they're circling this
beach where Zach washed up.

433
00:22:05,681 --> 00:22:07,481
- Alien birds?
- I don't know.

434
00:22:07,601 --> 00:22:09,601
If I could get hold of one
to analyse it...

435
00:22:09,721 --> 00:22:11,481
Good job I've got one
in my backpack.

436
00:22:11,601 --> 00:22:13,001
Picked it up
when I were in Peru.

437
00:22:13,121 --> 00:22:15,241
That's why you smell
of dead bird!

438
00:22:15,361 --> 00:22:16,761
I thought you'd changed
your shower gel.

439
00:22:16,881 --> 00:22:18,201
GRAHAM: Doc!

440
00:22:18,321 --> 00:22:20,641
Doc, Adam's in a bad way
in there.

441
00:22:20,761 --> 00:22:21,801
I think we made a mistake

442
00:22:21,921 --> 00:22:24,681
by disconnecting him from
all that gubbins in Hong Kong.

443
00:22:26,361 --> 00:22:28,801
Or maybe you just want to
stand out here watching birds.

444
00:22:28,921 --> 00:22:30,481
More like they're watching us.

445
00:22:30,601 --> 00:22:31,761
You go inside.

446
00:22:32,961 --> 00:22:34,081
I'll keep my eye on them.

447
00:22:34,201 --> 00:22:35,521
Let's take a look at Adam.

448
00:22:38,721 --> 00:22:40,761
Let us know
if anything changes, Aramu!

449
00:22:48,441 --> 00:22:49,881
GABRIELA: So I guess
you recognise me.

450
00:22:50,001 --> 00:22:51,161
YAZ: No.

451
00:22:52,601 --> 00:22:54,201
GABRIELA: Two Girls Roaming!

452
00:22:54,321 --> 00:22:55,761
I haven't seen it.

453
00:22:57,281 --> 00:22:58,641
What's the matter
with you people?

454
00:23:02,161 --> 00:23:05,401
(LABOURED BREATHING)

455
00:23:05,521 --> 00:23:06,841
YAZ: In here.

456
00:23:13,241 --> 00:23:14,841
Is that what we came for?

457
00:23:14,961 --> 00:23:15,881
Yeah.

458
00:23:16,001 --> 00:23:17,561
OK, so let's get out of here.

459
00:23:17,681 --> 00:23:19,361
It's connected
into the systems.

460
00:23:19,481 --> 00:23:21,401
I want to see what I can find.

461
00:23:21,521 --> 00:23:23,401
It looks like this lab

462
00:23:23,521 --> 00:23:26,201
is part of a triangulation
of signals

463
00:23:26,321 --> 00:23:28,761
with two other locations.

464
00:23:28,881 --> 00:23:31,161
One's Madagascar.

465
00:23:31,281 --> 00:23:32,961
Hide!

466
00:23:39,801 --> 00:23:42,401
YAZ: That's one
of the creatures Jake shot.

467
00:23:44,161 --> 00:23:45,361
GABRIELA: What is it doing?

468
00:23:49,041 --> 00:23:50,721
Whoa! Where did it go?

469
00:23:55,041 --> 00:23:56,601
What did it just do?

470
00:23:56,721 --> 00:23:58,441
It's a teleport station.

471
00:23:58,561 --> 00:23:59,841
We could follow it.

472
00:23:59,961 --> 00:24:01,561
Are you crazy?

473
00:24:02,681 --> 00:24:04,521
RYAN: So here's your present
from Peru.

474
00:24:07,721 --> 00:24:09,721
Ryan, will you dissect it
for me?

475
00:24:09,841 --> 00:24:10,921
What?!

476
00:24:11,041 --> 00:24:12,281
You must have done it
at school.

477
00:24:12,401 --> 00:24:13,681
Doesn't need to be elegant.

478
00:24:13,801 --> 00:24:15,601
Good! Cos it won't be.

479
00:24:15,721 --> 00:24:16,841
Nice lab.

480
00:24:16,961 --> 00:24:18,521
- Very well equipped.
- Thanks.

481
00:24:18,641 --> 00:24:19,841
Right. First things first.

482
00:24:19,961 --> 00:24:22,241
How are you off
for broad-spectrum antibiotics?

483
00:24:22,361 --> 00:24:23,441
- Yes, but only...
- Great!

484
00:24:23,561 --> 00:24:25,041
- ...a small supply.
- Graham!

485
00:24:25,161 --> 00:24:28,481
Jake. See if you can rig up
an IV.

486
00:24:28,601 --> 00:24:30,241
We need to get some medicine
into Adam,

487
00:24:30,361 --> 00:24:31,281
try and stabilise him.

488
00:24:31,401 --> 00:24:32,921
I have no idea how to do that.

489
00:24:33,041 --> 00:24:34,561
I'll give you a hand.

490
00:24:34,681 --> 00:24:37,121
I've seen a few
intravenous drips in my time.

491
00:24:37,241 --> 00:24:39,321
- Finally it comes in handy.
- I might need

492
00:24:39,441 --> 00:24:40,601
a high-powered microscope,

493
00:24:40,721 --> 00:24:42,681
blood cultures,
rapid genome sequencing,

494
00:24:42,801 --> 00:24:45,441
a spectrophotometer,
and a super-fast incubator.

495
00:24:45,561 --> 00:24:46,961
I've got most of that.

496
00:24:47,081 --> 00:24:49,801
Suki Cheng,
on a Madagascan beach,

497
00:24:49,921 --> 00:24:51,881
excellently equipped
and ready for anything.

498
00:24:52,001 --> 00:24:53,081
Ooh, can I use your computer?

499
00:24:54,481 --> 00:24:58,601
Right. I want to see
what's going on inside Adam.

500
00:24:58,721 --> 00:24:59,841
Gonna use your laptop

501
00:24:59,961 --> 00:25:02,921
to download the readings
I took from him earlier.

502
00:25:04,001 --> 00:25:06,441
- So what is it you do here?
- We're working on

503
00:25:06,561 --> 00:25:07,721
a marine filtration system

504
00:25:07,841 --> 00:25:09,401
connected into
the Crystal Oceans Initiative.

505
00:25:09,521 --> 00:25:12,041
Ah! Hence the water
filtration system.

506
00:25:12,161 --> 00:25:13,881
Micro version, is it?

507
00:25:14,001 --> 00:25:16,361
- You take a lot in very fast.
- Yes, I do.

508
00:25:16,481 --> 00:25:17,681
It's one of my skills.

509
00:25:17,801 --> 00:25:20,321
- (BEEP)
- Ah! Here we go.

510
00:25:20,441 --> 00:25:22,521
Initial blood analysis
for Adam.

511
00:25:30,961 --> 00:25:32,201
You OK, Doc?

512
00:25:36,281 --> 00:25:37,761
I'm sorry, Adam.

513
00:25:37,881 --> 00:25:39,801
Your bloodstream's
been infected

514
00:25:39,921 --> 00:25:41,601
with an alien pathogen,

515
00:25:41,721 --> 00:25:44,041
presumably in Hong Kong.

516
00:25:44,161 --> 00:25:47,161
Is it bad if I don't know
what a pathogen is?

517
00:25:47,281 --> 00:25:48,681
I'm glad you asked that,
cos I...

518
00:25:49,961 --> 00:25:51,921
- I didn't want to look stupid.
- It's a microorganism

519
00:25:52,041 --> 00:25:53,921
that carries disease.

520
00:25:54,041 --> 00:25:57,321
Alien bacteria, which is
latching on to life forms...

521
00:25:58,601 --> 00:26:00,281
...and killing them.

522
00:26:00,401 --> 00:26:02,561
I'm afraid it's inside you,
Adam,

523
00:26:02,681 --> 00:26:05,121
and right now I don't know how
we stop it overwhelming you.

524
00:26:16,361 --> 00:26:18,521
GABRIELA: You really want
to follow that creature.

525
00:26:19,761 --> 00:26:21,441
We're seriously
going to do this?

526
00:26:22,721 --> 00:26:24,161
Yeah.

527
00:26:24,281 --> 00:26:26,281
Without knowing
where we're going?

528
00:26:27,401 --> 00:26:28,401
Yeah.

529
00:26:30,761 --> 00:26:32,961
What's the worst place
we could end up?

530
00:26:33,081 --> 00:26:34,641
Long list.

531
00:26:34,761 --> 00:26:36,481
You don't want to know.

532
00:26:36,601 --> 00:26:38,361
You are crazy!

533
00:26:40,761 --> 00:26:42,401
Two girls roaming...

534
00:26:42,521 --> 00:26:43,801
Ready?

535
00:26:56,281 --> 00:26:58,161
I know you're worried
about your husband, mate,

536
00:26:58,281 --> 00:27:00,081
but he's in good hands
with the Doc.

537
00:27:01,441 --> 00:27:02,721
Just go away.

538
00:27:05,961 --> 00:27:09,441
What did he mean when he said,
"Seven months too late"?

539
00:27:14,841 --> 00:27:17,281
I was supposed to come out
and see him launch.

540
00:27:17,401 --> 00:27:19,721
Say goodbye
as he went off to the ISS.

541
00:27:21,401 --> 00:27:23,481
And you didn't go.

542
00:27:23,601 --> 00:27:25,961
He knew what he was taking on
with me.

543
00:27:26,081 --> 00:27:28,001
I don't do emotions.

544
00:27:29,161 --> 00:27:30,521
And I'm really not good at...

545
00:27:30,641 --> 00:27:32,921
...sticking with things,
you know? Commitment.

546
00:27:34,321 --> 00:27:37,001
Also, I really don't like
foreign travel.

547
00:27:37,121 --> 00:27:39,521
Wow. So you were
quite the catch, then.

548
00:27:43,921 --> 00:27:47,041
Yeah.
He's a lucky, lucky bloke.

549
00:27:48,761 --> 00:27:52,721
My husband is an astronaut.

550
00:27:52,841 --> 00:27:54,361
Do you have any idea
how hard it is

551
00:27:54,481 --> 00:27:56,681
being married to somebody
that impressive?

552
00:28:01,281 --> 00:28:02,721
It sort of sends me
the other way.

553
00:28:04,001 --> 00:28:05,761
I wallow in being unreliable.

554
00:28:05,881 --> 00:28:07,961
Like I'm punishing him.

555
00:28:08,081 --> 00:28:09,521
What for?

556
00:28:12,641 --> 00:28:13,921
Not being honest.

557
00:28:15,041 --> 00:28:16,761
No, sorry, you lost me.

558
00:28:16,881 --> 00:28:20,201
If he's that...impressive,
if he's that amazing...

559
00:28:22,361 --> 00:28:23,481
...which he is...

560
00:28:25,441 --> 00:28:27,361
...he can't love me
the way he says he does.

561
00:28:28,641 --> 00:28:30,881
It doesn't make sense.
Why would he?

562
00:28:35,161 --> 00:28:36,361
Oh, mate.

563
00:28:39,921 --> 00:28:41,801
I don't think he's the one
you're punishing.

564
00:28:52,681 --> 00:28:54,281
GABRIELA: We're still alive.

565
00:28:54,401 --> 00:28:56,121
We didn't die!

566
00:28:57,241 --> 00:28:59,841
Didn't teleport
into an active volcano.

567
00:28:59,961 --> 00:29:01,481
Result!

568
00:29:06,801 --> 00:29:08,121
What do you think this is?

569
00:29:08,241 --> 00:29:10,161
YAZ: Some sort of alien colony.

570
00:29:12,521 --> 00:29:13,721
Look at all this stuff.

571
00:29:16,161 --> 00:29:17,281
What even is it?

572
00:29:20,121 --> 00:29:22,361
If we're on an alien planet,

573
00:29:22,481 --> 00:29:23,881
then what is that?

574
00:29:37,841 --> 00:29:39,161
That...

575
00:29:40,561 --> 00:29:42,001
...is part of a submarine.

576
00:29:42,121 --> 00:29:43,361
SUKI: I've gene-sequenced

577
00:29:43,481 --> 00:29:45,401
blood cultures
from Adam and that bird.

578
00:29:45,521 --> 00:29:46,961
Wow, you are fast.

579
00:29:47,081 --> 00:29:48,761
If I track changes
in the optical density

580
00:29:48,881 --> 00:29:50,601
and confirm the bacteria's
growth rate,

581
00:29:50,721 --> 00:29:52,201
we might be able
to use that data

582
00:29:52,321 --> 00:29:54,001
to genetically engineer
a virus.

583
00:29:54,121 --> 00:29:55,401
That's what I was thinking!

584
00:29:55,521 --> 00:29:56,761
We're so sympa.

585
00:29:58,321 --> 00:30:01,721
(DOCTOR AND SUKI
CHAT QUIETLY)

586
00:30:03,001 --> 00:30:04,881
Hey.

587
00:30:07,561 --> 00:30:10,201
(CRUNCHING)

588
00:30:10,321 --> 00:30:12,081
The antibiotics aren't working!

589
00:30:12,201 --> 00:30:13,881
He's getting worse!

590
00:30:15,281 --> 00:30:16,361
GRAHAM: Doctor!

591
00:30:16,481 --> 00:30:18,401
Doc. Doc.

592
00:30:18,521 --> 00:30:20,801
Aramu says that the birds are
getting really angry out there.

593
00:30:20,921 --> 00:30:23,401
Not surprised, if this is
what their insides are like.

594
00:30:23,521 --> 00:30:25,441
Take a look.

595
00:30:25,561 --> 00:30:27,201
They're full of plastic.

596
00:30:27,321 --> 00:30:30,121
Once plastic gets in the ocean,
birds mistake it for food.

597
00:30:30,241 --> 00:30:32,081
I've seen hatchlings
regurgitate

598
00:30:32,201 --> 00:30:33,481
200 individual pieces.

599
00:30:33,601 --> 00:30:35,121
It's feasting on the plastic
in the birds

600
00:30:35,241 --> 00:30:36,601
and taking them over!

601
00:30:36,721 --> 00:30:39,041
The alien pathogens
attacked the plastic.

602
00:30:39,161 --> 00:30:41,681
The plastic metastasized
as if it was living.

603
00:30:41,801 --> 00:30:43,361
Oh...

604
00:30:43,481 --> 00:30:45,001
Autons?

605
00:30:45,121 --> 00:30:46,201
No, it can't be Autons.

606
00:30:46,321 --> 00:30:48,441
They don't work like this.
Not bacterial.

607
00:30:48,561 --> 00:30:50,761
Come on, brains! Move it along!

608
00:30:50,881 --> 00:30:52,041
(WHISPERS) Did she say "brains”
plural?

609
00:30:52,161 --> 00:30:53,841
How does that explain
what happened to Jamila?

610
00:30:53,961 --> 00:30:55,881
Like, she just got taken over.

611
00:30:56,001 --> 00:30:58,641
Yeah. How does it? It attacks
the plastic in the birds,

612
00:30:58,761 --> 00:31:00,521
but there's no plastic
in humans.

613
00:31:00,641 --> 00:31:01,721
Except...

614
00:31:01,841 --> 00:31:03,321
Oh!

615
00:31:03,441 --> 00:31:05,201
Microfiltration!

616
00:31:08,121 --> 00:31:10,321
Hey, Doc.
That's not a thought -

617
00:31:10,441 --> 00:31:12,041
- that's just a random phrase.
- No, no, no.

618
00:31:12,161 --> 00:31:13,841
That's a very big thought.

619
00:31:13,961 --> 00:31:17,601
The microfiltration system
in the water.

620
00:31:17,721 --> 00:31:20,201
- It filters out...
- BOTH: ...microplastics!

621
00:31:20,321 --> 00:31:21,881
Alien bacteria

622
00:31:22,001 --> 00:31:23,841
homing in on microplastics

623
00:31:23,961 --> 00:31:25,641
because humans
are full of them!

624
00:31:25,761 --> 00:31:27,321
Excuse me,
I'm not full of plastic.

625
00:31:27,441 --> 00:31:29,481
- Full of something.
- I'm afraid you are, Graham.

626
00:31:29,601 --> 00:31:32,801
It's in the air, it's in
your food, it's in your water.

627
00:31:32,921 --> 00:31:34,681
Humans have flooded this planet
with plastics

628
00:31:34,801 --> 00:31:37,201
that can't be fully
broken down, so much so

629
00:31:37,321 --> 00:31:39,521
that you're ingesting
micro particles,

630
00:31:39,641 --> 00:31:41,121
whether you know it or not!

631
00:31:41,241 --> 00:31:44,041
You're poisoning yourselves
as well as your planet.

632
00:31:44,161 --> 00:31:46,481
An alien bacteria
has come to this planet,

633
00:31:46,601 --> 00:31:48,401
and it found a feast.

634
00:31:52,161 --> 00:31:54,641
(BIRDS SQUAWKING)

635
00:32:11,201 --> 00:32:12,921
(YELLS)

636
00:32:16,761 --> 00:32:18,241
Hey, Doc, let's get rid
of this bird,

637
00:32:18,361 --> 00:32:20,161
cos it really, really smells.

638
00:32:20,281 --> 00:32:22,361
No. Look!

639
00:32:22,481 --> 00:32:24,041
What?

640
00:32:27,681 --> 00:32:30,321
See what the bird's natural
enzymes are doing.

641
00:32:30,441 --> 00:32:32,441
Oh, yeah. Clear as mud.

642
00:32:32,561 --> 00:32:35,081
Planet Earth... So clever.

643
00:32:35,201 --> 00:32:38,401
Two strains from Peru
fighting back,

644
00:32:38,521 --> 00:32:40,721
ganging up on the bacteria,

645
00:32:40,841 --> 00:32:44,041
holding it back to allow
natural decomposition!

646
00:32:44,161 --> 00:32:46,281
Come on. Catch me up on this,
please.

647
00:32:46,401 --> 00:32:48,241
Ryan Sinclair picks up
a dead bird in Peru

648
00:32:48,361 --> 00:32:50,801
and might just
have saved the world.

649
00:32:50,921 --> 00:32:53,041
Well, I am here for you guys,
you know.

650
00:32:53,161 --> 00:32:55,321
If we isolate and boost
the enzyme, then splice them,

651
00:32:55,441 --> 00:32:56,921
we'd have one
supercharged virus.

652
00:32:57,041 --> 00:32:58,601
Yes, we would.

653
00:32:58,721 --> 00:33:01,041
Yaz, how are you doing?
Cos we've literally got

654
00:33:01,161 --> 00:33:03,761
the most exciting rotting bird
that I've ever seen.

655
00:33:03,881 --> 00:33:05,521
I don't want you to panic...

656
00:33:05,641 --> 00:33:07,921
...but we followed one of those
things through a teleport,

657
00:33:08,041 --> 00:33:09,601
and now I think
we're on an alien planet.

658
00:33:09,721 --> 00:33:11,441
Well, you don't do things
by halves.

659
00:33:11,561 --> 00:33:14,521
Also, I think we found
the missing submarine.

660
00:33:14,641 --> 00:33:17,281
Not sure how that got here.
Oh, and another thing.

661
00:33:17,401 --> 00:33:19,361
The lab in Hong Kong
was sending data

662
00:33:19,481 --> 00:33:20,961
to two locations.

663
00:33:21,081 --> 00:33:23,601
One in the middle
of the Indian Ocean...

664
00:33:23,721 --> 00:33:25,481
...but the other
is in Madagascar...

665
00:33:25,601 --> 00:33:28,361
...where you are...right now.

666
00:33:29,961 --> 00:33:31,001
Doctor.

667
00:33:31,121 --> 00:33:33,241
Doctor,
did you hear what I said?

668
00:33:34,361 --> 00:33:36,681
Yeah. Thanks, Yaz.

669
00:33:36,801 --> 00:33:38,441
Sit tight.

670
00:33:41,161 --> 00:33:42,401
Suki Cheng...

671
00:33:43,641 --> 00:33:46,641
...out here all alone
in an over-equipped lab.

672
00:33:46,761 --> 00:33:48,721
I should have spotted it
straight away.

673
00:33:48,841 --> 00:33:50,241
RYAN: What's happening?

674
00:33:50,361 --> 00:33:51,881
Where's Yaz?

675
00:33:52,001 --> 00:33:53,481
I was so worried
when you turned up,

676
00:33:53,601 --> 00:33:55,521
when you took him
from Hong Kong.

677
00:33:55,641 --> 00:33:57,521
But you've really helped.

678
00:33:57,641 --> 00:33:58,921
Got even more answers from you

679
00:33:59,041 --> 00:34:00,801
than we did from experimenting
on Adam.

680
00:34:00,921 --> 00:34:02,601
We call the infection Praxeus.

681
00:34:02,721 --> 00:34:05,561
Trust me - it's smart,
it's relentless,

682
00:34:05,681 --> 00:34:07,201
and it knows you're onto it.

683
00:34:08,921 --> 00:34:11,681
Oh, I'm a sucker
for a scientist!

684
00:34:11,801 --> 00:34:13,121
Where did she just go?

685
00:34:13,241 --> 00:34:16,361
(BIRDS SQUAWKING)

686
00:34:18,841 --> 00:34:20,561
- (SQUAWKING INTENSIFIES)
- (FLURRY OF WINGS)

687
00:34:20,681 --> 00:34:22,121
We need to get out of here.

688
00:34:24,121 --> 00:34:26,001
(SILENCE)

689
00:34:26,121 --> 00:34:27,801
Have they gone?

690
00:34:32,401 --> 00:34:34,281
- GRAHAM: Doc, come on!
- (FRENZIED SQUAWKING)

691
00:34:35,761 --> 00:34:38,841
- DOCTOR: Take cover!
- GRAHAM: Let's go!

692
00:34:38,961 --> 00:34:40,241
Come on!

693
00:34:40,361 --> 00:34:41,721
DOCTOR: We need to get out!

694
00:34:41,841 --> 00:34:43,961
Don't let them scratch you -
they'll infect you!

695
00:34:45,361 --> 00:34:47,921
- I need to get the samples!
- GRAHAM: Doctor, come on!

696
00:34:52,481 --> 00:34:53,961
This is why I don't go abroad!

697
00:34:55,561 --> 00:34:58,001
- GRAHAM: Let's go!
- Here!

698
00:34:58,121 --> 00:35:00,321
Doc, catch!

699
00:35:01,561 --> 00:35:03,161
Come on!

700
00:35:09,281 --> 00:35:11,401
(BIRDS SQUAWKING)

701
00:35:11,521 --> 00:35:12,721
DOCTOR: Head straight
for the TARDIS.

702
00:35:12,841 --> 00:35:14,281
- Quick as you can.
- RYAN: They've seen us!

703
00:35:14,401 --> 00:35:16,321
They're following!

704
00:35:16,441 --> 00:35:18,521
DOCTOR: Just keep running!

705
00:35:20,241 --> 00:35:22,121
In here, all of you.

706
00:35:22,241 --> 00:35:23,481
Come on, Ryan!

707
00:35:28,601 --> 00:35:30,641
Yaz, we're on our way. Locked
in on your comma dot signal.

708
00:35:30,761 --> 00:35:33,161
We're coming for you,
wherever you are.

709
00:35:34,201 --> 00:35:36,121
If Praxeus is being spread
by birds,

710
00:35:36,241 --> 00:35:39,041
it could get around the world
incredibly fast,

711
00:35:39,161 --> 00:35:41,801
attacking and infecting
every living thing.

712
00:35:43,161 --> 00:35:45,761
We may potentially have a cure,
but we don't know if it works.

713
00:35:45,881 --> 00:35:47,401
Test it on me.

714
00:35:48,601 --> 00:35:50,761
No. Too dangerous.

715
00:35:50,881 --> 00:35:52,961
It's too dangerous
if we don't do it.

716
00:35:53,081 --> 00:35:55,721
You said yourself
there's no time.

717
00:35:57,601 --> 00:35:59,721
You need a clinical trial,
a human body,

718
00:35:59,841 --> 00:36:00,801
and now you've got one.

719
00:36:00,921 --> 00:36:03,401
- No.
- We don't have time to argue.

720
00:36:04,841 --> 00:36:07,161
JAKE: Adam, no. No way.
I'm not gonna let you!

721
00:36:07,281 --> 00:36:09,481
ADAM: It's not your choice
to make.

722
00:36:11,361 --> 00:36:12,361
(GASPS)

723
00:36:14,401 --> 00:36:15,881
Yaz.

724
00:36:16,001 --> 00:36:17,001
Look.

725
00:36:18,081 --> 00:36:19,561
Looks like it was
trying to get somewhere

726
00:36:19,681 --> 00:36:20,801
but its injuries were too bad.

727
00:36:20,921 --> 00:36:22,481
I wanna know what they are.

728
00:36:31,361 --> 00:36:32,721
Oh, my God!

729
00:36:33,801 --> 00:36:35,241
DOCTOR: Bioreadings synced

730
00:36:35,361 --> 00:36:36,841
with the TARDIS.

731
00:36:39,361 --> 00:36:43,241
If the antidote works on you,
the TARDIS will make more.

732
00:36:43,361 --> 00:36:44,801
Sure?

733
00:36:44,921 --> 00:36:46,601
Stop faffing about.

734
00:36:47,961 --> 00:36:49,481
(WHIRRING)

735
00:36:52,481 --> 00:36:54,041
(GASPS)

736
00:36:54,161 --> 00:36:55,921
(TARDIS THRUMS)

737
00:36:57,321 --> 00:36:58,841
We've landed.

738
00:36:58,961 --> 00:37:00,801
But where?

739
00:37:03,961 --> 00:37:06,561
Stay in here.
We'll be as quick as we can.

740
00:37:06,681 --> 00:37:08,001
With me.

741
00:37:11,481 --> 00:37:15,001
(DOOR OPENS AND CLOSES)

742
00:37:16,561 --> 00:37:19,201
God, you look miserable
right now.

743
00:37:24,441 --> 00:37:26,001
DOCTOR: Yaz! Found you.

744
00:37:26,121 --> 00:37:28,801
Thanks for coming to get us.
Eventually!

745
00:37:28,921 --> 00:37:30,601
Look at you, going off on your
own and not getting killed!

746
00:37:30,721 --> 00:37:31,761
Plus, totally found

747
00:37:31,881 --> 00:37:33,201
- an alien colony.
- (WHIRRING)

748
00:37:34,361 --> 00:37:36,121
Sort of.
It is an alien construct,

749
00:37:36,241 --> 00:37:37,761
but it's not an alien colony.

750
00:37:37,881 --> 00:37:39,801
RYAN: Then where are we?

751
00:37:39,921 --> 00:37:42,001
DOCTOR: A long way below
the Indian Ocean.

752
00:37:47,081 --> 00:37:49,961
Beneath a gyre
of plastic pollution.

753
00:37:50,081 --> 00:37:52,401
- We're under the sea?!
- It's a naturally occurring

754
00:37:52,521 --> 00:37:54,881
hot spot where ocean currents
trap pollution.

755
00:37:55,001 --> 00:37:57,681
There are five major gyres
on Earth right now.

756
00:37:57,801 --> 00:37:59,961
Praxeus is attracted
to plastic.

757
00:38:00,081 --> 00:38:02,601
It's built a whole environment
here from the plastic,

758
00:38:02,721 --> 00:38:04,801
a world of pure Praxeus!

759
00:38:04,921 --> 00:38:06,561
This is where it all started.

760
00:38:06,681 --> 00:38:09,161
Seabirds infected with Praxeus

761
00:38:09,281 --> 00:38:11,881
transporting the bacteria
around the world,

762
00:38:12,001 --> 00:38:13,841
transferring it to humans

763
00:38:13,961 --> 00:38:15,681
- when they attack!
- But how does

764
00:38:15,801 --> 00:38:17,441
an alien bacteria
end up in the Indian Ocean

765
00:38:17,561 --> 00:38:19,441
- in the first place?
- (WHIRRING)

766
00:38:19,561 --> 00:38:21,641
There's something else
down here,

767
00:38:21,761 --> 00:38:24,241
and I think it's connected
to our friend Suki.

768
00:38:24,361 --> 00:38:26,001
Come on.

769
00:38:28,201 --> 00:38:30,321
What are you
looking like that for?

770
00:38:30,441 --> 00:38:33,441
Thought I'd discovered
an alien planet on my own.

771
00:38:37,641 --> 00:38:39,481
We're at the bottom
of the Indian Ocean?

772
00:38:59,401 --> 00:39:00,561
How are you feeling?

773
00:39:03,921 --> 00:39:05,441
Dying.

774
00:39:07,761 --> 00:39:09,641
Not allowed.

775
00:39:09,761 --> 00:39:11,961
Dying man's wish.

776
00:39:28,001 --> 00:39:30,801
Stop dodging life.

777
00:39:33,161 --> 00:39:34,641
Please.

778
00:39:44,001 --> 00:39:46,121
YAZ: We followed it
through the teleport...

779
00:39:46,241 --> 00:39:48,041
...and found it here.

780
00:39:50,081 --> 00:39:51,681
DOCTOR: Humanoid.

781
00:39:51,801 --> 00:39:54,881
But not human.
Infected with Praxeus,

782
00:39:55,001 --> 00:39:56,561
but the body
hasn't disintegrated.

783
00:39:56,681 --> 00:39:58,441
Must be due
to the different biology.

784
00:39:58,561 --> 00:39:59,881
I don't get it.

785
00:40:00,001 --> 00:40:01,761
Why were these guys
experimenting on Adam?

786
00:40:01,881 --> 00:40:04,001
Maybe for the same reasons
we are.

787
00:40:04,121 --> 00:40:05,561
To find a cure.

788
00:40:09,041 --> 00:40:11,041
- (CRUNCHING)
- (GROANS)

789
00:40:12,521 --> 00:40:14,321
What does all this stuff mean?

790
00:40:14,441 --> 00:40:17,641
(BEEPING AND WHIRRING)

791
00:40:17,761 --> 00:40:20,641
(ALARMS BLARE)

792
00:40:23,201 --> 00:40:24,961
(GASPS)

793
00:40:30,121 --> 00:40:31,961
DOCTOR: Going somewhere?
Who were they, Suki?

794
00:40:32,081 --> 00:40:34,361
The infected people
in the hazmat suits?

795
00:40:36,841 --> 00:40:38,121
My crew.

796
00:40:38,241 --> 00:40:39,881
I'm the last one left.

797
00:40:40,001 --> 00:40:42,241
Wait. That's a spaceship,
right?

798
00:40:42,361 --> 00:40:43,841
DOCTOR: Well, the back end
of one, yes.

799
00:40:43,961 --> 00:40:46,441
Just when I thought things
couldn't get any madder.

800
00:40:47,241 --> 00:40:50,481
- Ooh.
- How did you get here?

801
00:40:51,921 --> 00:40:53,161
I was going to ask you
the same question,

802
00:40:53,281 --> 00:40:56,881
but I presume that ship is how.
So the question is...why?

803
00:40:58,761 --> 00:41:01,321
Praxeus devastated my planet.

804
00:41:01,441 --> 00:41:03,161
The survivors
were assigned to lab ships

805
00:41:03,281 --> 00:41:06,041
to find an antidote
for the few of us left alive.

806
00:41:07,361 --> 00:41:08,961
You're infected too.

807
00:41:09,081 --> 00:41:11,121
Cellular mutation
is slower for us.

808
00:41:11,241 --> 00:41:12,601
If you're scientists
in lab ships,

809
00:41:12,721 --> 00:41:14,001
please tell me you didn't

810
00:41:14,121 --> 00:41:16,401
bring this infection here
deliberately.

811
00:41:19,841 --> 00:41:22,041
Praxeus breeds in plastic,

812
00:41:22,161 --> 00:41:24,201
and this planet
is saturated in it.

813
00:41:24,321 --> 00:41:25,961
We travelled across
three galaxies to find

814
00:41:26,081 --> 00:41:27,521
the perfect living laboratory.

815
00:41:27,641 --> 00:41:30,121
To use Earth as a Petri dish,

816
00:41:30,241 --> 00:41:33,121
destroying one race to save
the remnants of your own!

817
00:41:34,361 --> 00:41:36,441
But this down here,
this environment,

818
00:41:36,561 --> 00:41:38,161
it wasn't deliberate.

819
00:41:39,481 --> 00:41:41,121
We lost control of the shuttle
on entry.

820
00:41:41,241 --> 00:41:42,161
Crash-landed.

821
00:41:42,281 --> 00:41:45,321
The bacteria flooded out,
irradiated, formed this world.

822
00:41:45,441 --> 00:41:48,281
And a broken spacecraft

823
00:41:48,401 --> 00:41:51,361
sending out pulses of energy
from the bottom of the ocean

824
00:41:51,481 --> 00:41:54,081
was enough to down and frazzle
a returning space capsule.

825
00:41:54,201 --> 00:41:57,841
This is the centre of where
everything's been happening!

826
00:41:57,961 --> 00:42:00,721
Your arm. You've been scratched
by those birds.

827
00:42:00,841 --> 00:42:02,961
You've had a double dose
of Praxeus.

828
00:42:03,081 --> 00:42:04,681
But you showed me
how to find a cure!

829
00:42:04,801 --> 00:42:06,681
Thanks to you, my mission
was successful. They already

830
00:42:06,801 --> 00:42:08,761
have the transmission
of how the cure could work.

831
00:42:08,881 --> 00:42:10,801
No! Suki, the cure is designed
for humans,

832
00:42:10,921 --> 00:42:12,961
and we don't even know
if it works on them.

833
00:42:13,081 --> 00:42:14,081
If you're not human,

834
00:42:14,201 --> 00:42:16,081
who knows what will happen?

835
00:42:17,201 --> 00:42:19,521
Please tell me you haven't
administered it on yourself.

836
00:42:22,321 --> 00:42:23,641
Stay out of my way.

837
00:42:26,761 --> 00:42:28,241
Stay here.

838
00:42:33,081 --> 00:42:34,561
Suki! Listen to me!

839
00:42:34,681 --> 00:42:36,241
We can work together on this.

840
00:42:36,361 --> 00:42:38,081
- Get out of here!
- I wouldn't use that in here.

841
00:42:38,201 --> 00:42:40,321
Not with those reverse-pulse
proton engines.

842
00:42:40,441 --> 00:42:42,881
Very unreliable.
No wonder you crashed.

843
00:42:44,521 --> 00:42:46,681
- Put that thing down!
- Sortable, though.

844
00:42:46,801 --> 00:42:48,641
Organic fuel cells.

845
00:42:49,681 --> 00:42:52,081
Oh, hang on.
I'm having half a thought.

846
00:42:52,201 --> 00:42:54,521
Ooh! This one tickles.
What is it?

847
00:42:54,641 --> 00:42:56,561
Oh! Yes!

848
00:42:56,681 --> 00:42:59,841
You can store anything
in organic fuel cells -

849
00:42:59,961 --> 00:43:02,641
anything vaguely organic!
Look at us, Suki.

850
00:43:02,761 --> 00:43:05,001
- (CRUNCHING)
- Two brilliant scientists -

851
00:43:05,121 --> 00:43:06,161
we can fix this!

852
00:43:06,281 --> 00:43:09,041
Work together, find a cure
for you, and then we can

853
00:43:09,161 --> 00:43:11,361
stop Earth from being
taken over by Praxeus!

854
00:43:12,761 --> 00:43:15,081
(CRUNCHING)

855
00:43:15,201 --> 00:43:17,281
What's happening to me?!

856
00:43:17,401 --> 00:43:18,761
It's spreading!
How do I stop it?

857
00:43:18,881 --> 00:43:20,561
(WHIMPERS)

858
00:43:20,681 --> 00:43:22,401
Help me!

859
00:43:22,521 --> 00:43:23,521
(GASPS)

860
00:43:32,241 --> 00:43:35,081
You OK? Where's Suki?

861
00:43:35,201 --> 00:43:37,841
Succumbed to Praxeus.
But I think this may

862
00:43:37,961 --> 00:43:40,201
give us a way through.
I need a crew in here.

863
00:43:41,481 --> 00:43:43,201
- Count us in.
- Hi.

864
00:43:44,921 --> 00:43:46,881
Turns out...

865
00:43:47,001 --> 00:43:48,681
...it worked.

866
00:43:49,961 --> 00:43:51,881
- Your machine spat this out.
- That's the antidote.

867
00:43:52,001 --> 00:43:53,961
And by the way,
where the hell are we?

868
00:43:54,081 --> 00:43:56,601
Follow me! Lots to do.

869
00:43:56,721 --> 00:43:58,481
Engine vents on. Apparently.

870
00:43:58,601 --> 00:44:01,121
System set to automated
timed venting. I think.

871
00:44:01,241 --> 00:44:03,081
Manual bypass...bypassed.

872
00:44:03,201 --> 00:44:05,041
Dials on full clockwise.

873
00:44:05,161 --> 00:44:07,041
- I said anticlockwise!
- Just testing!

874
00:44:07,161 --> 00:44:09,961
Organic fuel cells
loaded with Praxeus antidote.

875
00:44:10,081 --> 00:44:13,441
Trajectory aligned. Comms off.
Spatial regulators disabled.

876
00:44:13,561 --> 00:44:16,801
Organic fuel cells filled
with Praxeus-killing virus,

877
00:44:16,921 --> 00:44:19,201
as tested on Adam, check.

878
00:44:19,321 --> 00:44:22,361
Autopilot system set
for the Earth's stratosphere,

879
00:44:22,481 --> 00:44:25,561
check. All systems set
for automation.

880
00:44:25,681 --> 00:44:28,001
No idea what any of this means,
but is that literally

881
00:44:28,121 --> 00:44:29,401
the controls for up, down,
left and right?

882
00:44:29,521 --> 00:44:30,561
Yeah.

883
00:44:30,681 --> 00:44:32,841
Adam Lang, your job is so easy!

884
00:44:32,961 --> 00:44:34,801
Shuttle initiating
autopilot take-off.

885
00:44:36,201 --> 00:44:37,841
Gold stars
for my apprentice engineers.

886
00:44:37,961 --> 00:44:39,601
What is actually happening?!

887
00:44:39,721 --> 00:44:42,161
Once the ship
is in the stratosphere,

888
00:44:42,281 --> 00:44:45,681
the engines discharge the virus
in one superpowered burst,

889
00:44:45,801 --> 00:44:49,721
dispersing it around the world,
killing Praxeus stone dead.

890
00:44:49,841 --> 00:44:51,281
Hopefully.

891
00:44:51,401 --> 00:44:53,481
Only one tiny flaw in the plan.

892
00:44:53,601 --> 00:44:56,041
Send this into the atmosphere,
it'll rip a hole in this world,

893
00:44:56,161 --> 00:44:59,361
and we'll be crushed under
the entire Indian Ocean.

894
00:44:59,481 --> 00:45:01,641
That's more than a tiny flaw,
Doc!

895
00:45:01,761 --> 00:45:03,881
And that's why
I set the autopilot.

896
00:45:04,001 --> 00:45:05,481
So everybody out, now.

897
00:45:09,041 --> 00:45:11,081
Go!

898
00:45:13,521 --> 00:45:15,761
- What was that?
- Autopilot failure.

899
00:45:15,881 --> 00:45:17,001
It can't connect.

900
00:45:17,121 --> 00:45:17,961
It's gonna work, though, right?

901
00:45:18,081 --> 00:45:19,641
I don't know. It might not.

902
00:45:19,761 --> 00:45:21,041
But it's definitely going
to take off.

903
00:45:21,161 --> 00:45:22,241
We need to get out of here!

904
00:45:22,361 --> 00:45:23,361
JAKE: What if it doesn't work?!

905
00:45:23,481 --> 00:45:25,441
Too late to fix! Come on.

906
00:45:30,081 --> 00:45:32,601
Got to be fast taking off!

907
00:45:36,601 --> 00:45:37,881
Where's Jake?

908
00:45:41,081 --> 00:45:43,441
- Where's Jake?!
- YAZ: He was right behind us.

909
00:45:43,561 --> 00:45:44,521
JAKE: Are these comms on?

910
00:45:44,641 --> 00:45:46,521
Spacecraft to blue box -
can you hear me?

911
00:45:48,161 --> 00:45:49,561
Jake, what are you doing?!

912
00:45:49,681 --> 00:45:51,521
Manual pilot making up
for broken autopilot.

913
00:45:53,841 --> 00:45:56,121
Any idiot can fly a spaceship,
right?

914
00:45:56,241 --> 00:45:57,801
Jake...

915
00:45:57,921 --> 00:45:59,961
I don't want this.

916
00:46:00,081 --> 00:46:01,841
Maybe 7 do.

917
00:46:03,161 --> 00:46:04,321
Maybe I need this.

918
00:46:04,441 --> 00:46:06,721
You're entering
into the stratosphere!

919
00:46:08,241 --> 00:46:11,281
Yeah, that really doesn't
mean anything to me!

920
00:46:11,401 --> 00:46:13,041
But if I was a betting man -

921
00:46:13,161 --> 00:46:14,961
and my husband would tell you
I really am -

922
00:46:15,081 --> 00:46:17,721
I'd say the automatic release
is bust.

923
00:46:17,841 --> 00:46:19,601
Tell me what I need to do!

924
00:46:19,721 --> 00:46:22,281
The controls by your right hand
will vent the antidote.

925
00:46:22,401 --> 00:46:25,441
You need to flick
the three switches at once.

926
00:46:25,561 --> 00:46:27,121
I'm going to give it a go!

927
00:46:28,041 --> 00:46:29,761
The ship's gonna break up.

928
00:46:29,881 --> 00:46:30,761
DOCTOR: Jake, you have to wait

929
00:46:30,881 --> 00:46:32,241
until the shuttle's
in the right position.

930
00:46:32,361 --> 00:46:34,201
Adam?

931
00:46:36,401 --> 00:46:37,521
Adam!

932
00:46:37,641 --> 00:46:39,801
I'm sorry I wasn't
at the launch.

933
00:46:41,321 --> 00:46:43,681
This is me not dodging.

934
00:46:45,161 --> 00:46:47,201
Don't say
I never listened to you!

935
00:46:47,321 --> 00:46:48,641
DOCTOR:
Shuttle's in position, Jake.

936
00:46:51,001 --> 00:46:52,281
Dispersing antidote...

937
00:46:52,401 --> 00:46:53,761
.I think.

938
00:46:55,881 --> 00:46:58,801
DOCTOR: Jake, you've done it!
Antidote particles

939
00:46:58,921 --> 00:47:01,241
being dispersed into
the jet streams.

940
00:47:01,361 --> 00:47:02,481
Hope it works!

941
00:47:05,481 --> 00:47:07,001
Ship's very knackered!

942
00:47:08,401 --> 00:47:10,281
About to blow!

943
00:47:10,401 --> 00:47:11,601
You can save him, right?

944
00:47:11,721 --> 00:47:13,361
Oh...

945
00:47:14,561 --> 00:47:16,481
(EXPLOSION)

946
00:47:16,601 --> 00:47:19,361
(ALARMS BLARE)

947
00:47:19,481 --> 00:47:20,321
Doc, come on!

948
00:47:29,361 --> 00:47:31,881
(TARDIS THRUMS)

949
00:47:43,161 --> 00:47:44,601
I hate you.

950
00:47:47,601 --> 00:47:49,201
Yes, I can save him.

951
00:47:49,321 --> 00:47:51,241
Just...
if I materialise around him

952
00:47:51,361 --> 00:47:53,361
in the millisecond
before the ship breaks up.

953
00:47:53,481 --> 00:47:54,721
Nice work, Doc.

954
00:47:54,841 --> 00:47:56,401
What can I say?

955
00:47:56,521 --> 00:47:58,481
I'm a romantic.

956
00:48:10,921 --> 00:48:12,321
DOCTOR: I guess
this is goodbye, then.

957
00:48:12,441 --> 00:48:13,841
YAZ: Keep the planet safe
for us.

958
00:48:13,961 --> 00:48:16,481
Cos we'll be coming back,
so it'd better be in good nick.

959
00:48:16,601 --> 00:48:18,161
Or we'll know who to blame!

960
00:48:18,281 --> 00:48:21,401
- Thank you.
- Our pleasure. Really.

961
00:48:21,521 --> 00:48:22,761
Although I have to say,

962
00:48:22,881 --> 00:48:24,801
worst thing about
saving the human race -

963
00:48:24,921 --> 00:48:26,321
nobody knows it was me.

964
00:48:26,441 --> 00:48:28,201
Least I could get was a statue!

965
00:48:28,321 --> 00:48:30,561
So what's the plan now
for you two?

966
00:48:30,681 --> 00:48:32,841
Dunno.
Spend some time together.

967
00:48:34,081 --> 00:48:35,081
We never had a honeymoon,

968
00:48:35,201 --> 00:48:36,441
because he didn't want
to go abroad.

969
00:48:36,561 --> 00:48:37,641
Maybe now's the time.

970
00:48:37,761 --> 00:48:39,241
- I'll come with you!
- How's that a honeymoon

971
00:48:39,361 --> 00:48:40,601
if you're with us?

972
00:48:40,721 --> 00:48:42,121
We can vlog about it!

973
00:48:42,241 --> 00:48:44,081
What you gonna call it?
Three Id jots Roaming?

974
00:48:44,201 --> 00:48:45,761
I like it! It's snappy!

975
00:48:45,881 --> 00:48:47,041
And factual.

976
00:48:47,161 --> 00:48:48,921
Yeah, you guys can go now.

977
00:48:49,041 --> 00:48:50,801
We'll take the planet
from here.

978
00:48:51,921 --> 00:48:52,921
Hey!

979
00:48:53,041 --> 00:48:54,681
Come find us some time.

980
00:48:56,881 --> 00:48:58,161
DOCTOR: Planet Earth.

981
00:48:58,281 --> 00:48:59,801
Seven billion lives,

982
00:48:59,921 --> 00:49:02,761
separate and connected.

983
00:49:02,881 --> 00:49:04,761
From the edge of
the atmosphere

984
00:49:04,881 --> 00:49:07,201
to the depths of the ocean.

985
00:49:40,041 --> 00:49:41,041
DOCTOR: Welcome to Aleppo!

986
00:49:41,161 --> 00:49:44,961
MAN: Your worst fears.
My creativity.

987
00:49:45,081 --> 00:49:46,201
Who are you?

988
00:49:46,321 --> 00:49:48,801
Get everyone out.

